SIMPLE: prevaricate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prevaricate
<hw>Pre*var"i*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Prevaricated</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Prevaricating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>praevaricatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>praevaricari</ets> to walk
crookedly, to collude; <ets>prae</ets> before + <ets>varicare</ets> to
straddle, fr. <ets>varicus</ets> straddling, <ets>varus</ets> bent. See
<er>Varicose</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To shift or turn from one
side to the other, from the direct course, or from truth; to speak with
equivocation; to shuffle; to quibble; <as>as, he <ex>prevaricates</ex>
in his statement</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>prevaricates</qex> with his own understanding.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Civil Law)</fld> <def>To collude, as where an
informer colludes with the defendant, and makes a sham
prosecution.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld> <def>To undertake a thing falsely
and deceitfully, with the purpose of defeating or destroying
it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To evade; equivocate; quibble; shuffle.</syn>
<usage> -- <er>Prevaricate</er>, <er>Evade</er>, <er>Equivocate</er>.
One who <xex>evades</xex> a question ostensibly answers it, but really
turns aside to some other point. He who <xex>equivocate</xex> uses words
which have a double meaning, so that in one sense he can claim to have
said the truth, though he does in fact deceive, and intends to do it. He
who <xex>prevaricates</xex> talks all round the question, hoping to
⟦ldquo⟧dodge⟦rdquo⟧ it, and disclose nothing.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prevaricate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prevaricate
<hw>Pre*var"i*cate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To evade by a quibble; to
transgress; to pervert.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Jer.
Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prevarication</ent>⟦br⟧
